        mDrawable.draw(canvas);
    }

    // ...
}
```

In this example, when `onSizeChanged()` is called, a new instance of `MyDrawable` is created and its bounds are set to match the size of the view. Then, a runnable is created and posted using the `post(Runnable)` method. The runnable updates the `MyDrawable` object and invalidates the view, triggering a redraw. 

The drawable object is then drawn in the `onDraw()` method by calling its `draw()` method on the `Canvas` object passed to `onDraw()`.

If you try to cast a `View`'s `getParent()` result to a `LinearLayout` and it is not an instance of `LinearLayout`, a `ClassCastException` will be thrown.

The `ClassCastException` is a runtime exception that can occur when you try to cast an object to a type that is not compatible with its actual type. It extends the `RuntimeException` class, which means that it is an unchecked exception and does not need to be handled by a `catch` block (although it can be caught and handled if desired). 

Here's an example of how a `ClassCastException` might be caught when trying to cast a `View`'s `getParent()` result to `LinearLayout`:

```java
