ViewGroup parent = (ViewGroup) myView.getParent();
if (parent instanceof LinearLayout) {
  LinearLayout linearLayout = (LinearLayout) parent;
  // do something with linearLayout
} else {
  // handle case where parent is not a LinearLayout
  Log.e(TAG, "Parent is not a LinearLayout");
}
```

In this example, the `getParent()` result is first cast to a `ViewGroup`, which is the parent class of all view groups. Then, an `instanceof` check is used to determine if the parent is a `LinearLayout`. If it is, the cast to `LinearLayout` is performed and the `linearLayout` variable can be used. If it is not, an error message is logged.

Catching the `ClassCastException` certainly provides a simpler alternative to checking the `instanceof` the parent and handling the case where it is not a `LinearLayout`. It allows you to write more concise code, since you only need to cast the parent to `LinearLayout` and handle the resulting exception if it occurs.

Here's an example of how you could use a `try`-`catch` block to cast the `getParent()` result to `LinearLayout` and handle the `ClassCastException`:

```java
View myView = findViewById(R.id.my_view);
try {
    LinearLayout linearLayout = (LinearLayout) myView.getParent();
    // do something with linearLayout
} catch (ClassCastException e) {
    // handle case where parent is not a LinearLayout
    Log.e(TAG, "Parent is not a LinearLayout", e);
}
```

This code tries to cast the `getParent()` result directly to `LinearLayout`. If the parent is not an instance of `LinearLayout`, a `ClassCastException` is thrown and caught in the `catch` block. In the `catch` block, you can handle the case where the parent is not a `LinearLayout`. 

Note that catching the exception can result in more concise code, but it can also make it harder to debug since it can hide issues that result in runtime exceptions. It's generally recommended to use exceptions sparingly and only handle those that are likely to occur and for which you have a clear plan for how to handle them.

To post a `Runnable` that calls `requestLayout()` on `inputContainer` the next time it is drawn, you can use the `postOnAnimation(Runnable)` method on `inputContainer`. This method posts the `Runnable` to the message queue that will be executed after the current frame is drawn.

Here's an example of how to use `postOnAnimation(Runnable)` to request a layout on `inputContainer` the next time it is drawn:

```java
